  "definitions": [
    "(transitive) to scorch, singe or burn\nil sole scotta la pelle ― the sun burns the skin",
    "(transitive, by extension, cooking) to boil or fry briefly (of meat or vegetables)",
    "(transitive, figurative) to deeply irritate; to insult; to offend\nquella battuta mi ha davvero scottatothat joke really insulted me",
    "(intransitive) to burn, to be hot\nil fornello scotta ― the burner is hot",
    "(intransitive, hyperbolic, by extension) (of a person or body part) to be excessively hot, especially because of a fever\nquel bambino scotta ― that boy is (excessively) hot",
    "(intransitive, figurative) to be of interest, to interest\ndomande che scottano ― burning questions",
    "(intransitive) to be precarious or in jeopardy\nla cattedra scottathe professorship is precarious",
    "(intransitive, figurative) to provoke displeasure\ntalvota la verità scottathe truth hurts sometimes"
  ],
  "description": "scottare",
  "etymology": "From Vulgar Latin *excoctāre, present active infinitive of *excoctō, derived from Latin excoctus, perfect passive participle of excoquō (“I boil; I melt; I dry up”), derived from coquō (“I cook”).",
